{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_iris_ver01/data/sn78002169/0027955890A/1946053101/0383.xml":{"full_text":"VETERANS CHANGE\nSE /ICE POLICIES\nOver $7 5 0, 0 0 0 Worth\nConverted Here Since\nJanuary 1, 1946\nThe local Veterans Administra\ntor Wilmington Contract office,\nlast night reported that since Janu\narv i, over $750,000 insurance has\nbeen re-instated and converted to\npermanent policies.\nThe announcement came on the\nfve of the day and night confer\nence scheduled to start this morn.\njng at 11 o\u2019clock in the Community\nCouncil chambers, fourth floor,\nfide Water building.\nE. C. Baker, regional insurance\nofficer for the VA, Winston-Salem,\njt.ivcd yesterday afternoon to at\ntend the conference and make an\ninspection of the local set up.\nHe said yesterday afternoon that\nthe local office was the first in\nthe state to keep daily records on\nveterans insurance accounts.\nInvited to attend the meeting this\nJXJTLOOK FOR GEORGIA PEACHES\nQuantity of Georgia Peach Crop Harvested Each Year\u201c\u201c*\"\u201c\nEach Bushel Equals 1,000,000 Bushels of Peaches\n1946\nEst.\n1945\n1944\n1943\n1942\n6.580.000\n8.091.000\n4.590.000\n1.593.000\n6.177.000\nTK&*.\nmorning are representatives of all\nlocal insurance companies, and all\nmembers of the legion and its af\nfiliate organizations.\nBaker is here to get Information\nconcerning the local contract of\nfice\u2019 work with government insur\nance for World War I vets, and\nthe National Service Life Insur\nance for veterans of the recent\nwar.\nRobert Matthews, contract rep\nresentative for the local offices,\nSpm'<? Skoals\nFresh vegetables and\nMorton's Salt\u2014at your grocer'$^K||^^v.\nWfie\" i*\nrains\nit pours\nPATRONIZE YOUR LOCAL MERCHANTS\nCOSTS LES S-S TAYS AT HOME\nBALLARD'S FLOUR\nPlain o Self-Rising\n5 Lb. 10 Lb.\nPackages\nNabisco\nRITZ CRACKERS\nLarge 01.\nPackage LIv\nNabisco\nHoney Maid Grahams\nLarge 1Q\nPackage Ivli\n\u201cYou\u2019ve Tried The Rest\nNow Try The Best!\u201d\nLINEN WHITE\nWASHING BLEACH\nt\nQuart 1Q\nBottle IOC\nClean your silver\nin 10 seconds without rubbing\nwith Dippo Silver Cleaner\nTENDER LEAF\n(tT TEA j\n4 Oz.\nPkg.\n2TEASPd'0N$\n\u00abIVE Vi YOUR DAILY\nNEEDS OF VITAMIN A, VITA\nMIN B\u201e VITAMIN D; VITAMIN 6,\nNIACIN AMIDE, IRON, CALCIUM,\nPHOSPHORUS\nLittle Darling\nCUT GREEN\nBEANS\nNo. 2 J8c\nCan\nYour Nearby Home Service Store Has Full Lines Of\nFLORIDA CITRUS JUICES\nStock Up NOW For The Hot Days Ahead!\nSEE OUR COMPLETE LINES\nSPEAKERS NAMED\nCHARLOTTE, May 30.\u2014(A1)\u2014 Dr.\nFrederic T. Peirce of N. C. State\ncollege and Dr. H. Y. Jennings\nof Danville, Va., originator of a\nfiber bonded process for cotton\nyarn, are among speakers for the\nsouthern textile association\u2019s an\nnual meeting scheduled to open\nnext Thursday at Myrtle Beach,\nS. C.\nBRICKER FLAYS TRUMAN\nGETTYSBURG, Pa., May 30\u2014\n(OT\u2014 John W. Bricker, the 1044\nRepublican nominee for vice presi\ndent, Thursday called president\nTruman\u2019s proposal to draft strikers\ninto the Army \u201cabhorent to the\nAmerican way of life.\u201d\nsaid last night the insurance is\nbroken down into three classes;\nordinary life; 20-year pay, and 30\nyear pay.\nFOR DELIGHTFUL MEALS\nGo To\nHANOVER INN\nDINING ROOM\nWrightsville Beach\nMrs. Elizabeth Pemberton Dean\nCHEERING NEWS\nSummer Business Outlook\nBright, Babson Declares\nNoted Economist Predicts\nGood Retail, Tourist\nTrade This Year\nBy ROGER W. BABSON\nBABSON PARK, Mass., May 30\nBusiness activity in the next few\nmonths should constantly improve\nin most lines. With newspapers full\nof uncertainties regarding politics\nand other depressing items, it is\na relief to focus one\u2019s attention\non the good news from the domes\ntic front.\nTextile mills have stepped up\nschedules since the German armies\ndestroyed many of the big mill\ncenters in Northern France and\nBelgium. Gray goods sales have\nbeen high and the demand for\nshirts and men's wear of all kinds\nis tremendous.\nStrike Setbacks\nSteel operations have been handi\ncapped by strikes of all kinds but\nnow have a green light to go ahead.\nMany thought the end of the war\nmight hit the steel industry harder\nthan most others, but it has not.\nInventories in consumers\u2019 hands\nare said to be lower than ever be\nfore.\nChemical industries are just be\nginning to feel the good effects of\nthe postwar program. How much\nthey will add to the business total\nin the next few months is uncer\ntain just now. Investors, business\nmen, and workers should, however,\nkeep in mind that this nation is\nentering upon a tremendous plas\ntic program which can be operat\ned with little feai of strikes. There\nfore, What is now on the books is\na mere sampling of what is to\nfollow in chemical developments.\nRetail Trade Gootl\nRetail trade is remarkably good.\nIt is running 25 per cent or more\n\u25a0above a year ago. This comparison\nwith 1945 levels comes from the in\ndustrial areas of the Middlewest,\nfrom the South and from the Paci\nfic Coast. Rising payrolls mean\nthat these gains should continue\nfor sometime to come. I am still\nbullish on merchandist securities\nas the best hedge against both\nwage increases and inflation.\nTourist business: Due to the hesti\ntancy of cruising even to the West\nIndies, South America, Alaska and\nCanada this summer. The greater\nefforts which the railroad and bus\nlines are making in developing\ntravel indicate that this Summer\nwill see the largest vacation sea\nson on record.\nThe business outlook for the Sum\nmer, therefore, is good. There will\nbe no set-backs due to cancellation\nof orders or psychological reac\ntions. Any change will be to in\ncrease an already high level of ac\ntivity. Hence, I believe that over\nall business this Summer should be\neven better than ever before. If\nyou plan a vacation away from\nhome, you better get your reser\nvations now.\nThe strike leaders have surely\noverplayed their hands. At last\noverplayed theiroverplayede.-uerbd\nthey got American poepleLa\naroused by their arrogance and\nindifference to the public welfare.\nI am sorry for this because I\nbelieve in intelligent collective\nbargaining wih arbitration as a last\nresort. But when a Lewis or a\nWhitney holds a pistol to our heads\nto force the signing of a contract,\nthis is revolution and insurrection.\nLet us hope Congress will make\nthis impossible to occur again.\nWASHES WOOLENS\nto fluffy softness\nAMERICA\u2019S WASH WORD 3\nMENU IDEA\nfotjoiy>y\nFrom the kitchens of Blue Plate Foods\nFruit-Filled\nPeanut Butter Cookies\n2 cups flour cup Nrw B!u\n2 teaspoons bak- Plate Peanut\nIng powder Butter\nt teaspoon salt 1 cup sugar\ncup fat 1 egg, beaten\ncup milk\nSift flour, baking' powder and salt.\nCream fat, sugar and Blue Plate\nPeanut Butter. (It\u2019s smoother than\never, richer in flavor!) Add egg and\nbeat until smooth. Add milk and\nflour alternately. Mix well. Roll\ndough i inch thick on floured board, and cut out with cookie\ncutter. Place half the cookies on greased cookie sheet and place\nteaspoon of fruit filling in center of each. Cover with another\ncookie and press edges firmly together. Bake in moderately\nhot oven until delicately browned.\nFilling: Use sweetened stewed raisins, apricots or apples.\nNew! Smoother\u2014and stays\nsmooth to the last spoonful\u2014\nRicher peanut flavor too!\nBLUE PLATE\nPeanut\nButter\nBLUE PLATE MEANS FINE FLAVO\n\u00aeA\nA 6.00 x 16 SIZE\nALLSTATE\nCOSTS |Q\nONLY I\nPlus Fed. Tax\nTHANKS TO SEARS SYSTEM OF\nSTRAIGHTLINE DISTRIBUTION\nRemember\nIt pays to wait. Our fac\ntories are going full steam\nahead\u2014shipments are go\ning forward daily. We\u2019re\ntrying to keep up with de\nmand. But even if our stock\nof tires is depleted, we will\ntake your order and ear\nmark it for delivery as soon\nas possible.\nTRUCK TIRES IN STOCK\n8.25x20-10 Ply 7.00x20\u201410 Ply\n7.00x15 6 Ply\nd.00x20\u20146 Ply 9.00x20-10 Ply\n7.50x20-10 Ply 10.00x20-12 Ply\nrr\nCOMPOUNDED OIL 45 PLATE BATTER